@Megan Comet
Hello. I'm Korean living in the United States.
First of all, I don't think that Korea has cheaper educational options than the other countries. I think it's about how Korean think education important relative to the other countries. If I compare the educational system between South Korea and the United States, Korean gov. offers free education till secondary school while US gov. offers free education till high school. But, In spite of that fact, In the historical context we had dramatically rapid economic, social growth after the Korean War. And one of the reasons that we could accomplish this growth is parents generations' hard work and focusing on future generations' education. They wanted to give us economically, socially better country. They thought the only way to succeed and contribute to country is to study hard and to get professional careers in terms of long-term growth. I think that fact impacted how our educational system is like. Also, because of this historical context, there are thoughts that teenagers should go high school after secondary school. To tell you my personal experience, almost all of my friends went to high school after they graduated middle school. I would say it's kind of against the conventional thoughts not to go high school. (But it's not about the whole Korean population! My parents doesn't think it's necessary to go high school or university.) And I think those two graphs shows well these facts. I hope my reply helped you. :)
